            {
               "text": "### The Birth of a Star\n\nThe image in this section shows a circle highlighting the region of the Milky Way where stellar formations can be seen within red clouds (<htcite0>).\n\n#### The Beginning\n\nThe formation of stars is a long and gradual process in the universe. It took around 300 million years for the first stars to appear (<htcite1>).\n\nFor a star to be born, a large cloud of cold dust composed mainly of Hydrogen (H) is necessary. From it, stars may form due to gravitational collapse (“matter coming together”) or from the pressure of gas heated by nearby stars (<htcite2>; <htcite3>; <htcite4>).\n\n#### The Collapse of Clouds\n\nInside these clouds, still cold — with temperatures around -240 ºC (-400 ºF) — nuclei made only of Hydrogen (H) atoms are formed. These nuclei begin to collide, heating the interior and gathering more matter. This process eventually leads to the formation of so-called “baby stars” (<htcite5>; <htcite6>; <htcite7>).\n\n#### The Formation of the Star\n\nAs matter collapses into the interior of the protostar, Hydrogen (H) atoms begin to fuse, creating Helium (He) atoms (<htcite8>). As for the dust that does not become part of the star, it tends to clump together, forming what we know as planets (<htcite9>).\n\nThis is a general view built from data collected by telescopes. However, since star formation takes thousands of years, the full process has never been observed directly (<htcite10>).\n\n#### Literature\n\nIt is not uncommon to find in ancient texts descriptions of stars and people forming almost spontaneously (<htcite11>; <htcite12>; <htcite13>). These accounts cannot be considered wrong, as they belong to the realm of literature. On the other hand, they reveal humanity’s desire to explain the universe—an aspiration that goes back thousands of years (<htcite14>).",
